purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book contributes to the growth of interest in task-based language learning and teaching that has been seen in recent years. It brings together research that focuses on various aspects and effects of pedagogic task design and presents work that uses tasks to examine oral interaction, written production, vocabulary and reading, lexical innovation and pragmatics in different formal language learning contexts and in different languages (English as a second/foreign language, French/German/Italian/Spanish as foreign languages). It also provides guidelines for task classification, sequencing and design. The book is addressed to both professionals and students interested in second language acquisition research. It will also be of use to professionals involved in language pedagogy and curriculum design.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aLanguage and languagesxStudy and teaching. 0aTask analysis in education. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / Psycholinguistics.2bisacsh  aSLA.  aSecond Language Acquisition.  aclassroom.  acurriculum design.  aformal language learning contexts.  alanguage pedagogy.  atask-based language learning.  atask-based language teaching.  avocabulary.1 aColina, Ana Alegría De La, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngler, Steve, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarcía Mayo, María del Pilar, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGarcía, Marisol Fernández, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilabert, Roger, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIshikawa, Tomohito, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuiken, Fo